---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Chemo-dynamical reconstruction of Milky Way globular cluster progenitors - Lardo et al. (2026)";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Chemo-dynamical reconstruction of Milky Way globular cluster progenitors</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Lardo et al. (2026)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Paper</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>First described:</th>
          <td>2026 (Lardo et al.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key Papers:</th>
          <td>
            <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11814">Lardo+2026 (arXiv:2603.11814)</a>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Abstract summary:</strong> Using homogeneous stellar parameters for 69 Galactic globular clusters derived while modelling multiple populations, the authors reconstruct progenitor-specific age--metallicity relations and test whether helium-related multiple-population properties depend on progenitor origin once cluster mass and metallicity are controlled for.</p>

    <h2>Key findings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Short enrichment timescales (τ ≲ 2 Gyr)</li>
      <li>Most progenitors reach Δ[Fe/H] ≈ 1.1–1.3 dex; Sagittarius reaches ≈1.6 dex</li>
      <li>Mass–MP scaling is universal; δY and mean Y do not depend on progenitor origin</li>
      <li>Sequoia clusters show higher f_P1 at fixed mass and metallicity</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Implications</h2>
    <p>AMRs carry signatures of progenitor chemical evolution. Helium enrichment amplitude is regulated by cluster mass and appears blind to environment, suggesting universal cluster-scale formation physics; a secondary environmental imprint remains in the enriched-star fraction.</p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Lardo, C., Valcin, D., Jimenez, R. (2026). "Chemo-dynamical reconstruction..." <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11814">arXiv:2603.11814</a></li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
